

1. Discuss law of demand and assumptions of law of demand.
The law of demand states that, all other things being equal, when the price of a good or service rises, the quantity demanded of that good or service falls. In a word, price and demand are negatively correlated. For example, if the price of smart phone increases the demand for it will decrease. But if the price goes down, the demand for it will go up. The phenomenon is basically due to two reasons namely substitution effect and income effect. Substitution effect occurs when consumers switch to cheaper substitute. Income effect is when the increase in price decreases consumers’ purchasing power.
The law of demand is based upon certain assumptions. It also assumes that other factors affecting demand are constant such as the income of the consumers, taste and preferences, prices of related good, expectations of the future and so forth. Nor does it assume large changes in the size and distribution of the population.  Another important assumption has been that consumers act rationally and try to maximize their satisfaction from the resources available to them. 
