Price elasticity of demand is a measure of how much the demand for a product changes when its price changes. Sensitivity is determined by quite a few important factors. "One of the big factors is the availability of substitutes. Demand will tend to be more elastic if there are close substitutes. If you raise your prices, customers will go elsewhere. Suppose that one brand of soft drink increases its price. Consumers could switch to another brand. However, for products like salt that have little or no substitutes, the substitutes’ demand is inelastic.
