How do firms make good pricing decisions in competitive markets with elasticity concepts?
The principle of price elasticity of demand can be used by firms to help improve their pricing strategies. This is particularly true in competitive markets where consumer reaction is important.  The price elasticity is a measure of how sensitive consumers are to changes in price . The business can then use this to adjust its strategies . If demand is elastic (consumers are elastic to price) companies should implement competitive or lower price strategies. In such cases, a slight rise in price could trigger a steep fall in sales. You have to keep your prices competitive or have discount to keep and attract customers. There are many substitutes for example in the clothing or electronics business. So companies use competitive pricing to boost demand.
Or, if demand is inelastic, the company can be more aggressive with price increases and have little impact on demand. This is the case of essential products or high brand loyalty products like pharmaceuticals or unique braded products etc.  Companies can increase their revenue through premium pricing strategies in this case. Elasticity helps firms decide whether to increase or decrease a price to increase or decrease total revenue, and thus control their revenue. If demand is elastic then a fall in price may cause total revenue to rise. If demand is inelastic, a price increase may increase total revenue.
Elasticity can also be used by companies to practice price discrimination. They can charge different prices to different customers depending on their sensitivity to price. Promotional approaches like discounting and seasonal pricing can also be shaped by demand trends. Finally, if firms know about elasticity they can price well, respond well to competition, and increase profits while giving consumers what they want.



2. Give the law of supply and its exceptions.
The law of supply states that, other things being equal (ceteris paribus), the quantity of a good supplied will increase as its price increases, and decrease as its price decreases. Basically there is a direct relationship between price and the supply. This is because high prices provide better profit opportunities for producers which incentivizes them to produce and sell a larger quantity of goods. Consider the price of wheat. If the price of wheat goes up, farmers have more incentive to grow and bring more wheat to market, so as to take advantage of the opportunity for higher profits.
