What Is the Phillips Curve and How Does It Impact Today’s Economies?

The Phillips Curve is an economic theory that shows the relationship between inflation and unemployment and that there is a trade-off between them. High inflation is usually associated with low unemployment in the short run. High demand for labour pushes up wages and the higher wages are passed on in the price of products. But high unemployment means less demand in the economy and that keeps inflation in check. The relationship was discovered by A.W Phillips and has become a vital tool in the policy makers armoury for balancing inflation and employment. 
But modern economies have been very critical of the Phillips curve in the standard form. Economists have discovered that this trade-off does not always work in the long run. The curve does not work in stagflation (high inflation and high unemployment), for example. And so the augmented Phillips curve was created by expectations. Inflation expectations matter. If workers and firms expect higher inflation they will adjust wages and prices to reflect this, dampening the effect of policy .
Under the present economic environment in the world, globalization, technological improvements and government policies have weakened or increased the volatility of Phillips Curve. Central banks have moved to an inflation target rather than a trade off between inflation and unemployment.  The Phillips Curve, however, remains a useful device for understanding short-run economic dynamics despite its problems. It can assist policy makers to better understand the relationship between inflation and unemployment and how they affect economic stability.




